May 22 2009 	Great location at Fisherman's Wharf with easy MUNI access to North Beach.	I stayed here for a week with business in the Financial District; my previous stay a year and a half earlier was also for a week at the Courtyard at Fisherman's Wharf a block away from the Marriott. I found both to be very satisfactory.The Marriott is between North Point and Bay Street on Columbus Ave with easy MUNI access on two sides of the hotel. The number 10 on the North Point side of the hotel runs east to the Embarcadero then Battery, Samsome and past Market Street in the Financial District. Another MUNI on the Columbus Ave side of the hotel (I don't recall the number) goes through North Beach, but turns off at Stockton in the middle of a bunch of restaurants. Definitely consider scoping out Sodini's Green Valley on Green Street and Firenza.I found the hotel, my room and staff to be very satisfactory. I did not have meals there, so cannot comment on that aspect of the hotel. As with most Marriott hotels, the hotel restaurant / lounge serves their 'premium' brands, but pricing is similar to restaurants in the area and in North Beach.Another comment about the location, the North Beach Shopping Center is about 2 1/2 blocks away on Bay Street. There's a Safeway store there, if you like to browsing for food and stuff as I do (being a single guy). There's also a place called the Blue Mermaid on Jefferson Street the serves up a very cozy nautical breakfast experience. Tarantino's Restaurant is also on Jefferson Street; I seem to always go for the chowder for starters, have the steamed clams bordelaise and add the garlic bread (to soak up some broth) . . . wine makes this combo so tasty.happy travelsgmk	
