Feb 3 2009	Great location loved the bed	A friend booked us into the Marriott Fisherman's Wharf. Upon arrival, the doors of the car were opened for us, our bags removed from the trunk and the car whisked away into parking. There is only valet parking at this location with 24 hour in and out privileges.Check in was smooth and swift. Our room was located on the 5th floor. There was only one elevator working the entire time we were there due to renovations being made on the 3rd and 4th floors, but we never had a problem waiting long for one to arrive. While our view was mainly of the Hilton across the street, there was a lovely view of Coit Tower above it.The room contained a small coffee maker, water for $4.00 per bottle, an HDTV (with confusing and difficult menus to manipulate to get the channel desired), an iPod docking station/clock radio. a chair and foot rest, good sized desk area, small table, the standard nightstands and king sized bed. The bed was very comfortable. It had a featherbed mattress topper, down comforter, feather and synthetic pillows to choose from and a light blanket as well. The sheets were smooth and soft. There were several outlets in the room. Internet connections are available for a price, but one may print boarding passes at a dedicated terminal by the front desk for free which saved me a good deal of time at the airport.The bathroom toiletries are from Bath and Body Works and ours were an orange ginger scent. The shower had a large and tall shower head, but my friend felt the water pressure could be higher. The toilet had one of the loudest flushes either of us had ever heard from the other room, even with the door shut.For the most part the room was quiet. However, the doors to the rooms were hard to shut unless closed firmly, thus, one could hear doors shutting all up and down the halls. The ambient noise from outside was not overwhelming, but one could hear horns honking and traffic moving.The concierge, John, was a tremendous help. He called a few restaurants on a Saturday evening just after five trying to get us reservations. The place he suggested was Albona's in North Beach, just a few blocks away. He called and convinced their maitre 'd to get us in before their dinner rush began. We were able to walk right over, be seated and were treated quite well, in part because of John's assistance.The breakfast buffet was standard fare. The made to order omelets are the best thing about it! One of my sausage links was not cooked which was unpleasant. The coffee left a good deal to be desired. The fruit was fresh. The staff friendly.Overall, I would say the staff was extremely helpful and friendly. This property is in a great location - just a few minutes walk from Ghiradelli Square, Fisherman's Wharf, and North Beach and easy in and out for driving.	
Dec 28 2008	No complaints whatsoever	We got a nice deal of $75/ night on Priceline. Going rate on hotel's website was $169. All the rooms are non-smoking. The room is a decent size, nice and clean with a coffeemaker, fridge, free newspaper everyday. The beds are the absolute most comfortable beds ever, even more comfortable than the 5-star beds we had in Vegas. It's not really a pillowtop bed, but they put a very comfy cushion that made it so so comfortable. The carpet is a little dated but not a dump. TV is old tube but we didn't care for it. Front desk was extremely helpful with our questions. You can print borading passes in the reception too. No internet in the room but you can connect downstairs in their email stations. Buffet was pricey at $20pp. Go next door at Denny's inside Holiday Inn for a cheaper breakfast. Location of this hotel is fine. If you are looking to stay at Fisherman's Wharf, I suggest you try Priceline so you'll get the best bang for your buck. All the hotels in this area (Sheraton, Holiday Inn, Hyatt, Radisson, Argonaut, Tuscann Inn etc.) are close and walkable to one another, so it doesn't matter which one you get. We ate at Sabella and Trattore, kinda like a local's place just beside Alioto restaurant . Food is cheap and great but general ambience is lacking and the area is filthy. Franciscan Restaurant just across is classy but expensive. The views are spectacular but the menu lacks lobster. We had the halibut and sturgeon and they were cooked to perfection. The best oyster we had was in the marketplace in the Ferry building where they give you a container and sell each piece for $1.50 and then you can sit down there and devour it. Freshest oyster we ever had! WE did this after taking the San Fran Comprehensive shuttle tour (highly recomended). Overall, San Francisco is very romantic, I would go there again in a heartbeat! I wouldn't mind staying at Marriott again!	
